WEBVTT

00:02.335 --> 00:04.337
(beeping)

00:08.717 --> 00:10.927
{\an5}ORDERLY (over intercom):
He's waking up.

00:18.476 --> 00:20.562
Can you hear me, Mr. Hanks?

00:23.231 --> 00:24.441
What's going on?

00:24.524 --> 00:25.734
Try to relax.

00:25.817 --> 00:28.903
Do you know your name?

00:28.987 --> 00:30.905
Raff Hanks.

00:30.989 --> 00:32.198
Great.

00:32.281 --> 00:34.159
{\an5}Do you know who
the president is?

00:34.242 --> 00:36.786
<i>(crowd cheering)</i>

00:36.870 --> 00:38.288
{\an8}CROWD (chanting):
Four more years!

00:38.371 --> 00:42.000
{\an8}Four more years!
Four more years!

00:42.083 --> 00:43.835
{\an8}Four more years!

00:43.918 --> 00:47.589
Four more years!
Four more years!

00:47.672 --> 00:51.176
Four more years! Four more
years!

00:51.259 --> 00:53.344
Four more years!

00:53.428 --> 00:54.971
{\an3}MAURA:
Well, you did it.

00:55.054 --> 00:56.681
<i>We</i> did it.

00:56.765 --> 00:58.183
CROWD:
Four more years!

00:58.266 --> 00:59.517
Stevens did it.

00:59.601 --> 01:00.894
{\an1}All right.

01:00.977 --> 01:05.315
{\an1}But with our help.
Our numbers, our data.

01:05.397 --> 01:07.317
We gave him this election.

01:07.400 --> 01:08.777
Can you not jinx things?

01:08.860 --> 01:10.779
I mean, no one's even counted
any votes yet.

01:10.862 --> 01:13.198
Oh, God.
(clears throat)

01:13.281 --> 01:14.949
I almost forgot.

01:15.033 --> 01:17.619
{\an8}Guess what came
in the mail today.

01:17.702 --> 01:18.745
{\an9}Hmm.

01:18.828 --> 01:22.290
{\an5}Subtle.

01:18.828 --> 01:22.290
{\an1}They never thought Stevens
would get reelected.

01:22.373 --> 01:24.042
Especially not with me
running his campaign.

01:24.125 --> 01:24.876
They were wrong.

01:24.959 --> 01:27.170
Again, can you just
not jinx things?

01:27.253 --> 01:30.006
Come on, you've seen the polls.
You see the crowds?

01:30.089 --> 01:33.218
{\an1}We took the most unpopular
president in American history,

01:33.301 --> 01:35.178
and we turned it around.

01:35.261 --> 01:38.181
I want Justin Timberlake
to play me in the HBO movie.

01:38.264 --> 01:40.016
You really think they're going
to turn this into a movie?

01:40.099 --> 01:41.142
Of course they are.

01:41.226 --> 01:44.270
It's only the greatest comeback
in American history.

01:44.354 --> 01:47.065
Well, now you've
really jinxed things, so...

01:47.148 --> 01:50.109
Raff, Maura, the results
are coming in.

01:50.193 --> 01:51.361
The president wants to see you.

01:51.444 --> 01:53.655
CROWD:
Stevens! Stevens! Stevens!

01:53.738 --> 01:57.700
Stevens! Stevens!
Stevens! Stevens!

01:57.784 --> 02:00.995
It all started out so well.

02:01.079 --> 02:02.497
{\an5}ORDERLY:
Do you know why you're here,
Raff...

02:02.580 --> 02:04.541
who did this to you?

02:04.624 --> 02:07.377
Do you know where you are?

02:07.460 --> 02:09.253
Who are you?

02:09.336 --> 02:13.716
{\an5}I'm here by order of the
president of the United States.

02:13.800 --> 02:16.594
(sighs)
Then I'm fucked.

02:22.141 --> 02:23.810
Hey.

02:25.270 --> 02:26.938
(clears throat)

02:29.941 --> 02:31.734
Thanks.

02:29.941 --> 02:31.734
{\an3}Thank you.

02:34.612 --> 02:37.031
{\an1}STEVENS:
What the fuck, Raff?!

02:37.115 --> 02:38.700
Mr. President?

02:38.783 --> 02:41.578
They're saying
I just lost New York,

02:41.661 --> 02:44.038
lost New Jersey.

02:44.122 --> 02:46.082
I'm from fuckin' New Jersey.

02:46.165 --> 02:48.751
I'm Mr. Fuckin' New Jersey!

02:48.835 --> 02:50.753
{\an1}We're losing the whole
goddamn country!

02:50.837 --> 02:53.631
{\an5}No, my data says...

02:50.837 --> 02:53.631
Oh, your data's horseshit!

02:53.715 --> 02:55.550
I listened to you.

02:55.633 --> 02:58.052
{\an1}I listened to you.
Your numbers and your polls

02:58.136 --> 03:00.763
{\an1}and your fancy data
and your high-tech baloney.

03:00.847 --> 03:04.434
{\an1}And guess what.
I lost.

03:04.517 --> 03:07.103
I am a one-term joke.

03:07.186 --> 03:10.106
I'm a diaper filled
with baby shit,

03:10.189 --> 03:13.943
and it is all your fault!

03:14.027 --> 03:15.820
Fuck!

03:19.824 --> 03:22.869
{\an3}Raff, listen, it's gonna
be okay. All right?

03:22.952 --> 03:24.662
You can come back from this.

03:24.746 --> 03:27.248
I mean, you're the
wunderkind, right?

03:33.421 --> 03:35.006
{\an5}REPORTER (on TV):
Voters are angry.

03:35.089 --> 03:36.633
{\an5}After two years in office,
the president is facing

03:36.716 --> 03:38.968
{\an5}increasing criticism
for his handling of the economy,

03:39.052 --> 03:41.429
{\an5}increasing crime, the
environment, and foreign policy.

03:41.512 --> 03:43.139
{\an5}MAN:
I mean, the world is a mess.

03:43.222 --> 03:45.475
{\an5}And these politicians,
they're not helping anybody.

03:45.558 --> 03:46.851
{\an5}We should just throw out
the whole system,

03:46.935 --> 03:47.727
start over again.

03:47.810 --> 03:49.979
{\an5}Well, let me ask
my distinguished panel.

03:50.063 --> 03:52.023
{\an5}What should the president do
about the situation

03:52.106 --> 03:53.149
in the Middle East?

03:53.232 --> 03:54.651
Thanks for asking, Sam.

03:54.734 --> 03:56.986
{\an1}"Well, you're
one of the most admired

03:57.070 --> 03:58.321
political minds
in the business."

03:58.404 --> 04:01.532
That I am, Sam.

04:01.616 --> 04:03.618
That I am.

04:04.744 --> 04:06.871
I just can't pay my rent.

04:08.414 --> 04:11.250
Hey, buddy.

04:12.961 --> 04:14.671
You really ran
Stevens' campaign?

04:14.754 --> 04:18.341
I did. I ran it
right into the ground.

04:18.423 --> 04:19.509
(laughs)

04:23.596 --> 04:25.181
{\an5}REPORTER:
In lighter news...

04:25.264 --> 04:27.392
{\an1}Tommy, come on,
hit me with another.

04:27.475 --> 04:29.686
{\an5}...look no further than
11-year-old YouTube sensation

04:29.769 --> 04:30.812
Oliver Foley.

04:30.895 --> 04:35.525
{\an5}His latest video is racking up
millions of hits because

04:35.608 --> 04:38.069
Oliver's running for president.

04:38.152 --> 04:41.531
{\an5}Oh, hey, hi.
I'm Oliver Henry Foley,

04:41.614 --> 04:46.369
{\an5}and I'm announcing my candidacy
for president of the USA.

04:46.452 --> 04:49.831
{\an5}Here's why. I want people
to be nice to each other.

04:49.914 --> 04:52.208
{\an5}I really do.
I know it sounds cheesy,

04:52.291 --> 04:53.459
but it's the truth.

04:53.543 --> 04:57.088
{\an5}And it's a good enough reason
to run for president as any.

04:57.171 --> 04:59.507
{\an5}I also believe that
everyone should go to school

04:59.590 --> 05:00.883
and play video games,

05:00.967 --> 05:03.052
{\an5}because it's good
for your hand-eye coordination.

05:03.136 --> 05:06.556
{\an5}I may be a kid,
but I sure do get America.

05:06.639 --> 05:09.851
{\an5}It's the land of equality
and freedom for everyone.

05:09.934 --> 05:12.061
Except maybe my little sister.

05:12.145 --> 05:13.938
You should run
that kid's campaign.

05:14.022 --> 05:17.191
{\an5}He tells it like it is.

05:14.022 --> 05:17.191
That's crazy.

05:17.275 --> 05:18.776
Eight million views crazy.

05:18.860 --> 05:21.738
Considering all the crap
coming out of Washington,

05:21.821 --> 05:23.031
{\an3}I'd vote for that kid
in a heartbeat.

05:23.114 --> 05:25.950
Me, too.
I like what he's saying.

05:26.034 --> 05:28.578
He's a little cutie.

05:34.959 --> 05:38.629
Meet Raff Hanks, a wunderkind.

05:38.713 --> 05:40.923
Once the most successful
campaign manager

05:41.007 --> 05:42.592
of his generation.

05:42.675 --> 05:46.763
Now Raff finds himself
in a valley of booze and regret.

05:46.846 --> 05:51.100
One filled with bad choices
and even worse polling.

05:51.184 --> 05:54.771
He's about to embark on
a misguided road to redemption.

05:54.854 --> 05:56.731
And on his way back to the top,

05:56.814 --> 05:59.025
he'll have to take a dark detour

05:59.108 --> 06:01.319
through The Twilight Zone.

06:03.863 --> 06:04.989
<i>(The Twilight Zone</i> theme
playing)

06:05.073 --> 06:07.283
NARRATOR: <i> You're traveling</i>
<i>through another dimension,</i>

06:07.366 --> 06:10.912
<i>a dimension not only of</i>
<i>sight and sound but of mind.</i>

06:10.995 --> 06:14.123
<i>It is the middle ground</i>
<i>between light and shadow,</i>

06:14.207 --> 06:16.918
<i>between science</i>
<i>and superstition.</i>

06:17.001 --> 06:19.462
{\an8}<i>And it lies between</i>
<i>the pit of one's fears</i>

06:19.545 --> 06:22.298
{\an8}<i>and the summit</i>
<i>of one's knowledge.</i>

06:22.381 --> 06:25.551
<i>You are now traveling through</i>
<i>a dimension of imagination.</i>

06:25.635 --> 06:29.472
<i>You've just crossed over</i>
<i>into The Twilight Zone.</i>

06:33.434 --> 06:37.980
{\an5}ORDERLY:
Mr. Hanks, you did
a great service for our country.

06:38.064 --> 06:39.857
Jesus.

06:39.941 --> 06:42.110
Our country?

06:42.193 --> 06:44.821
I saw an angle, man.

06:44.904 --> 06:46.989
I saw my shot, I took it.

06:47.073 --> 06:48.991
(monitor beeping rapidly)

06:50.576 --> 06:53.412
(groaning)

07:22.441 --> 07:25.987
{\an8}Mmm. This really is delicious.

07:26.070 --> 07:27.822
{\an7}Mmm.

07:26.070 --> 07:27.822
{\an9}OLIVER:
Tuesdays is spaghetti,

07:27.905 --> 07:28.823
{\an8}and Wednesdays
is hamburgers.

07:28.906 --> 07:30.408
{\an8}Cheeseburgers.

07:30.491 --> 07:31.909
{\an8}Cheeseburgers,
if you're into that.

07:31.993 --> 07:34.579
{\an8}Can you pass the
Parmesan cheese?

07:34.662 --> 07:37.081
{\an8}Oliver.

07:34.662 --> 07:37.081
{\an7}Yeah?

07:37.165 --> 07:38.833
{\an9}Do you really want
to be president?

07:38.916 --> 07:42.170
{\an8}Yep. I'm sick of
all the war stuff

07:42.253 --> 07:44.672
{\an7}and the environment stuff
and the fact that

07:44.755 --> 07:47.133
{\an8}everybody lies all the time

07:47.216 --> 07:49.177
{\an8}and that we only get two weeks
off at Christmas break.

07:49.260 --> 07:50.261
{\an8}Wait.

07:50.344 --> 07:51.971
{\an9}If Oliver gets
to be president,

07:52.054 --> 07:53.347
{\an8}do I get to be vice president?

07:53.431 --> 07:55.308
{\an9}Uh, maybe, honey.
Eat your salad.

07:56.601 --> 07:58.728
{\an7}I first started
my YouTube channel

07:58.811 --> 08:01.439
{\an7}because my friend Charlie had
one, and I wanted one, too.

08:01.522 --> 08:03.733
{\an8}Then I started vlogging
about <i> Minecraft,</i>

08:03.816 --> 08:05.234
{\an8}which was sort of boring
because <i> Minecraft</i> is

08:05.318 --> 08:07.862
{\an9}for little kids, and
I'm not little anymore.

08:07.945 --> 08:09.739
{\an8}Then I started vlogging
about <i> Fortnite,</i>

08:09.822 --> 08:10.907
{\an8}which got me a bunch of views.

08:10.990 --> 08:13.576
{\an7}But then I decided
to run for president,

08:13.659 --> 08:16.412
{\an8}and I got 12 million views.

08:16.495 --> 08:18.372
{\an8}And then you showed up.

08:18.456 --> 08:20.374
{\an8}And then I showed up.

08:20.458 --> 08:22.460
{\an8}What'd I just say?

08:23.628 --> 08:28.049
{\an8}HELEN:
Really, Raff, why are you here?

08:28.132 --> 08:30.218
{\an7}I know this thing has
gotten a lot of coverage,

08:30.301 --> 08:32.303
{\an8}but he's a kid, it's a joke.

08:32.385 --> 08:33.888
{\an7}Not to me.

08:33.971 --> 08:36.265
{\an7}People are really responding
to what Oliver is saying.

08:36.349 --> 08:38.226
{\an9}He's 11.

08:36.349 --> 08:38.226
{\an8}It's a technicality.

08:38.308 --> 08:39.809
{\an9}(laughs)
To being president.

08:39.894 --> 08:41.729
{\an7}Listen, your name will
be on the ballot.

08:41.812 --> 08:42.938
{\an7}He'll just be
the one in charge.

08:43.022 --> 08:47.109
{\an8}Oh. This is getting
better and better.

08:47.193 --> 08:49.403
{\an8}Listen, A-Andrew Johnson
was a tailor.

08:49.487 --> 08:51.280
{\an8}Teddy Roosevelt was a rancher.

08:51.364 --> 08:52.949
{\an8}Jimmy Carter was
a peanut farmer.

08:53.032 --> 08:54.492
{\an8}This country is very open

08:54.575 --> 08:56.786
{\an8}to leaders
without political baggage.

08:56.869 --> 09:00.456
{\an8}Raff, I googled you.
I did some research.

09:00.539 --> 09:02.792
{\an8}I know you've had a hard run.
You battled the booze...

09:02.875 --> 09:07.755
Joseph, I'm off it, completely.
I am a new man.

09:07.838 --> 09:11.259
I mean, I am drinking chamomile
tea, for the love of Pete.

09:11.342 --> 09:14.762
Well, still, we see what
you're trying to do here.

09:16.347 --> 09:18.307
You're an opportunist.

09:18.391 --> 09:20.851
Of course I am.

09:22.562 --> 09:25.314
I need this.

09:25.398 --> 09:27.942
This is what I do.

09:28.025 --> 09:30.319
But Oliver, your son,
has tapped into

09:30.403 --> 09:32.947
something very, very real.

09:33.030 --> 09:34.448
He connects with people.

09:35.741 --> 09:37.535
Do you realize how rare
that is in politics,

09:37.618 --> 09:39.662
to actually connect with people?

09:40.913 --> 09:43.708
I honestly believe
Oliver can be president.

09:43.791 --> 09:44.709
Come on, now...

09:44.792 --> 09:47.545
{\an1}And win or lose, when
all this is said and done,

09:47.628 --> 09:49.797
he will have had the experience
of a lifetime.

09:49.880 --> 09:52.216
{\an1}And he will have made enough
money from endorsements

09:52.300 --> 09:54.885
{\an1}and TV deals and book deals
to pay for his college

09:54.969 --> 09:57.888
and Lily's college,
the dog's college.

09:58.723 --> 10:01.017
You'll have your face
back on TV.

10:01.100 --> 10:02.852
{\an1}Exactly.

10:02.935 --> 10:05.855
{\an1}Everybody wins,
nobody gets hurt.

10:05.938 --> 10:08.399
This is the American dream.

10:10.443 --> 10:12.361
We're making a new video.
Lily's gonna film it.

10:12.445 --> 10:14.155
You want to watch?
It's gonna be awesome.

10:16.115 --> 10:17.700
{\an1}(sighs)

10:17.783 --> 10:19.952
(all laughing)

10:21.954 --> 10:23.873
(monitor beeping)

10:23.956 --> 10:26.751
(groaning)

10:26.834 --> 10:28.627
{\an6}LILY:
Go.

10:26.834 --> 10:28.627
Go?

10:28.711 --> 10:30.046
{\an3}Yes.

10:28.711 --> 10:30.046
Now?

10:30.129 --> 10:32.548
{\an6}Go now.

10:30.129 --> 10:32.548
Okay. Here are the ten things

10:32.631 --> 10:36.052
I promise the American people
if I'm elected president.

10:36.135 --> 10:38.721
Oh. Hi, Homer.

10:38.804 --> 10:41.349
This is Homer. Anyways,

10:41.432 --> 10:44.018
number one: jobs.
Jobs for everyone.

10:44.101 --> 10:48.064
{\an3}Number two: long weekends,
longer vacations.

10:48.147 --> 10:51.067
Number three:
less <i> Star Wars</i> movies.

10:51.150 --> 10:53.194
Number four:
better air to breathe,

10:53.277 --> 10:55.863
which means more bikes
and less cars.

10:55.946 --> 10:58.407
(over megaphone):
Number five: less war.

10:58.491 --> 11:02.286
Number six: dogs for dog people
and cats for cat people.

11:02.370 --> 11:03.913
Number seven:

11:03.996 --> 11:06.332
more pancake houses
throughout the land, please.

11:06.415 --> 11:10.753
Number eight: free video games
for every American!

11:10.836 --> 11:14.256
Number nine: every month has
to have its own holiday.

11:14.340 --> 11:17.468
Number ten:
dessert is before dinner!

11:17.551 --> 11:19.595
(cheering, applause)

11:19.678 --> 11:22.098
Got hot dogs waiting on the bus.
Ketchup and mustard.

11:22.181 --> 11:23.766
The little juice boxes
like you like.

11:23.849 --> 11:25.267
And baby carrots?

11:25.351 --> 11:27.937
Of course. With ranch dressing.
I'm no monster.

11:28.020 --> 11:30.398
We got CNN and Fox
this afternoon,

11:30.481 --> 11:31.774
Rachel Maddow tonight.

11:31.857 --> 11:33.275
{\an3}She's nice.

11:33.359 --> 11:34.860
Super nice.
And you promised me

11:34.944 --> 11:36.278
the interview
with the <i> Times,</i> remember?

11:36.362 --> 11:37.905
{\an3}Only if we can stop
at the water park

11:37.988 --> 11:39.281
on the way back
to the airport.

11:39.365 --> 11:41.617
You got it.

11:41.700 --> 11:43.577
Hey, what about the song?

11:43.661 --> 11:44.787
And the music video?

11:44.870 --> 11:47.081
I get a lot of views
with my videos.

11:47.164 --> 11:48.958
Recording studio booked,
dancers are rehearsing.

11:49.041 --> 11:51.419
{\an1}It's been
two months now.

11:51.502 --> 11:54.171
You can do better, Raff.

11:54.255 --> 11:55.631
You're right.

11:55.714 --> 11:57.633
I can do better.

11:57.716 --> 11:58.843
{\an3}MAURA:
Wow.

11:58.926 --> 12:00.636
{\an1}The wunderkind
and the wunderkind.

12:00.719 --> 12:03.305
Maura McGowan.

12:03.389 --> 12:05.808
{\an3}What are you doing here on the
mean streets of rural Iowa?

12:05.891 --> 12:09.311
{\an1}I saw your mug on TV,
figured I'd come say hi.

12:09.395 --> 12:11.355
You want to get the band back
together again, don't you?

12:13.607 --> 12:16.777
I wrote you off after Stevens.

12:16.861 --> 12:18.154
I was wrong.

12:18.237 --> 12:19.822
"I was wrong."

12:19.905 --> 12:21.532
My three favorite words
in the English language.

12:21.615 --> 12:23.826
Okay, don't push it.

12:23.909 --> 12:25.327
You know you missed me, Maura.

12:25.411 --> 12:27.621
A little bit.

12:31.041 --> 12:34.170
Good. Come on.

12:34.253 --> 12:37.339
{\an4}MAURA:
So what are we going to do,
though, when it all, you know,

12:37.423 --> 12:38.799
blows up in our faces?

12:38.883 --> 12:40.885
(Raff laughs)

12:46.640 --> 12:48.851
{\an5}ORDERLY:
Look, Mr. Hanks,

12:48.934 --> 12:51.854
{\an5}we're going to have to operate.
Your condition is not stable.

12:51.937 --> 12:55.649
I'm not sure that I ever was.

12:55.733 --> 12:58.986
A stable person would've seen
what was happening.

12:59.069 --> 13:01.197
♪<i> Hey, hey, hey</i> ♪

13:01.280 --> 13:02.698
♪ Let's hit it ♪

13:02.781 --> 13:05.326
♪ We the people
all across the nation ♪

13:05.409 --> 13:08.662
♪ It's about time
for a celebration ♪

13:08.746 --> 13:11.874
♪ Bright future
is the new sensation ♪

13:11.957 --> 13:14.376
♪ Time to break free
like summer vacation ♪

13:14.460 --> 13:17.713
♪ Put your hands up
if you feel that, whoa ♪

13:17.796 --> 13:19.089
{\an5}♪ If you had enough... ♪

13:17.796 --> 13:19.089
{\an1}Hey.

13:19.173 --> 13:21.383
{\an5}Hey.

13:19.173 --> 13:21.383
{\an1}Those national ads
done yet?

13:21.467 --> 13:23.219
{\an5}We have that TV space on hold.

13:21.467 --> 13:23.219
{\an3}Almost.

13:23.302 --> 13:25.387
{\an3}Oliver hasn't signed off yet
completely, but he will.

13:25.471 --> 13:27.389
{\an3}He will.

13:25.471 --> 13:27.389
{\an1}I hope so.

13:27.473 --> 13:30.059
{\an3}You know, his last set of
notes were four pages long,

13:30.142 --> 13:31.894
